25|$|The {{prosecution}} argued that, after {{committing the}} murders {{to secure a}} large inheritance, Bamber had placed <b>the</b> <b>gun</b> <b>in</b> {{the hands of his}} 28-year-old sister, who had been diagnosed with schizophrenia, to make the scene appear to be a murder–suicide. Convicted by a 10–2 majority, Bamber is serving life imprisonment without the possibility of parole. As of November 2016 he was one of 70 prisoners in the UK subject to a whole-life order.|$|E
